            No. Stellar Intel never holds user funds, user keys, fiat, or KYC data. You sign every transaction in your own wallet; the anchor takes custody under SEP-24/SEP-6; Stellar enforces atomicity.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt
            id="faq-heading-1"
          >
            <button
              aria-controls="faq-panel-1"
              aria-expanded="false"
              class="flex w-full items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 text-left text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-inset focus-visible:ring-blue-600 dark:text-white dark:hover:bg-gray-800/60"
              type="button"
            >
              <span>
                What happens if an anchor fails or doesn't pay out?
              </span>
              <svg
                aria-hidden="true"
                class="lucide lucide-chevron-down ml-4 h-4 w-4 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200 dark:text-gray-400"
                fill="none"
                height="24"
                stroke="currentColor"
                stroke-linecap="round"
                stroke-linejoin="round"
                stroke-width="2"
                viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                width="24"
                xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              >
                <path
                  d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"
                />
              </svg>
            </button>
          </dt>
          <dd
            class="px-5 pb-4 pt-0 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400"
            hidden=""
            id="faq-panel-1"
          >
            The anchor — not Stellar Intel — is the settlement party. We surface that risk before you choose: each anchor carries a reputation score built from real outcomes (fill rate, slippage, settle latency). A failing anchor ranks down and its failures are recorded. If an outcome is wrong, you can file a dispute, which resolves on signed, replayable evidence.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt
            id="faq-heading-2"
          >
            <button
              aria-controls="faq-panel-2"
              aria-expanded="false"
              class="flex w-full items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 text-left text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-inset focus-visible:ring-blue-600 dark:text-white dark:hover:bg-gray-800/60"
              type="button"
            >
              <span>
                How is this different from a block explorer or a single anchor's app?
              </span>
              <svg
                aria-hidden="true"
                class="lucide lucide-chevron-down ml-4 h-4 w-4 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200 dark:text-gray-400"
                fill="none"
                height="24"
                stroke="currentColor"
                stroke-linecap="round"
                stroke-linejoin="round"
                stroke-width="2"
                viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                width="24"
                xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              >
                <path
                  d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"
                />
              </svg>
            </button>
          </dt>
          <dd
            class="px-5 pb-4 pt-0 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400"
            hidden=""
            id="faq-panel-2"
          >
            We compare live rates across every integrated anchor and rank by net landed value (rate − fees − slippage − historical fill-rate penalty), not headline rate — then let you execute in one click. Plus a public reputation oracle and an MCP agent surface. It's the execution layer, not just a price page.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt
            id="faq-heading-3"
          >
            <button
              aria-controls="faq-panel-3"
              aria-expanded="false"
              class="flex w-full items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 text-left text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-inset focus-visible:ring-blue-600 dark:text-white dark:hover:bg-gray-800/60"
              type="button"
            >
              <span>
                Why did anchor X not show up in the comparison?
              </span>
              <svg
                aria-hidden="true"
                class="lucide lucide-chevron-down ml-4 h-4 w-4 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200 dark:text-gray-400"
                fill="none"
                height="24"
                stroke="currentColor"
                stroke-linecap="round"
                stroke-linejoin="round"
                stroke-width="2"
                viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                width="24"
                xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              >
                <path
                  d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"
                />
              </svg>
            </button>
          </dt>
          <dd
            class="px-5 pb-4 pt-0 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400"
            hidden=""
            id="faq-panel-3"
          >
            Most often: the anchor doesn't serve that corridor, or it only exposes a SEP the rate engine doesn't yet quote. Historically SEP-6-only anchors were dropped because the flow was SEP-24-only — SEP-6 support is being added. Failed anchors render as "unavailable" rather than disappearing silently.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt
            id="faq-heading-4"
          >
            <button
              aria-controls="faq-panel-4"
              aria-expanded="false"
              class="flex w-full items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 text-left text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-inset focus-visible:ring-blue-600 dark:text-white dark:hover:bg-gray-800/60"
              type="button"
            >
              <span>
                Which corridors and anchors are supported?
              </span>
              <svg
                aria-hidden="true"
                class="lucide lucide-chevron-down ml-4 h-4 w-4 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200 dark:text-gray-400"
                fill="none"
                height="24"
                stroke="currentColor"
                stroke-linecap="round"
                stroke-linejoin="round"
                stroke-width="2"
                viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                width="24"
                xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              >
                <path
                  d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"
                />
              </svg>
            </button>
          </dt>
          <dd
            class="px-5 pb-4 pt-0 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400"
            hidden=""
            id="faq-panel-4"
          >
            See the anchor registry in constants/anchors.ts and the live app. Coverage expands via the anchor onboarding process.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt
            id="faq-heading-5"
          >
            <button
              aria-controls="faq-panel-5"
              aria-expanded="false"
              class="flex w-full items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 text-left text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-inset focus-visible:ring-blue-600 dark:text-white dark:hover:bg-gray-800/60"
              type="button"
            >
              <span>
                Can an AI agent off-ramp through this?
              </span>
              <svg
                aria-hidden="true"
                class="lucide lucide-chevron-down ml-4 h-4 w-4 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200 dark:text-gray-400"
                fill="none"
                height="24"
                stroke="currentColor"
                stroke-linecap="round"
                stroke-linejoin="round"
                stroke-width="2"
                viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                width="24"
                xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              >
                <path
                  d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"
                />
              </svg>
            </button>
          </dt>
          <dd
            class="px-5 pb-4 pt-0 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400"
            hidden=""
            id="faq-panel-5"
          >
            Yes — an MCP server exposes pricing/comparison and a user-signed execute path. The agent cannot move funds on its own; every executing call must be signed by the user's wallet.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt
            id="faq-heading-6"
          >
            <button
              aria-controls="faq-panel-6"
              aria-expanded="false"
              class="flex w-full items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 text-left text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-inset focus-visible:ring-blue-600 dark:text-white dark:hover:bg-gray-800/60"
              type="button"
            >
              <span>
                Is there an SDK?
              </span>
              <svg
                aria-hidden="true"
                class="lucide lucide-chevron-down ml-4 h-4 w-4 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200 dark:text-gray-400"
                fill="none"
                height="24"
                stroke="currentColor"
                stroke-linecap="round"
                stroke-linejoin="round"
                stroke-width="2"
                viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                width="24"
                xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              >
                <path
                  d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"
                />
              </svg>
            </button>
          </dt>
          <dd
            class="px-5 pb-4 pt-0 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400"
            hidden=""
            id="faq-panel-6"
          >
            A typed client (@stellarintel/sdk) is on the roadmap (v4). Today you can call the HTTP API directly.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt
            id="faq-heading-7"
          >
            <button
              aria-controls="faq-panel-7"
              aria-expanded="false"
              class="flex w-full items-center justify-between px-5 py-4 text-left text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-inset focus-visible:ring-blue-600 dark:text-white dark:hover:bg-gray-800/60"
              type="button"
            >
              <span>
                How do I contribute?
              </span>
              <svg
                aria-hidden="true"
                class="lucide lucide-chevron-down ml-4 h-4 w-4 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200 dark:text-gray-400"
                fill="none"
                height="24"
                stroke="currentColor"
                stroke-linecap="round"
                stroke-linejoin="round"
                stroke-width="2"
                viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                width="24"
                xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              >
                <path
                  d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"
                />
              </svg>
            </button>
          </dt>
          <dd
            class="px-5 pb-4 pt-0 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400"
            hidden=""
            id="faq-panel-7"
          >
            Read CONTRIBUTING.md, pick a good-first-issue, and open a PR. The docs/COOKBOOK.md has end-to-end recipes.
          </dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </section>
  </section>
</div>
`;
